 statement made by us is past contradiction. It is exactly on these lines tha\ntM mighty sale wtll be conducted THURSDAY, MAY 28th 'till Saturday June 13th Every\nanicS fn our st will be marked in plain figures. The broadest\nguarantee in all America covers every article.\nSATISFACTION GUARANTEED OR YOUR MONEY REFUNDED.\nThe doors will be closed Tuesday and Wednesday, May 26th and 27th, and will remain closed\nuntil Thursday, May 28th, so as to enable us to mark down and arrange this stock for the big crowd\nwhich will surely flock to our doors.\n27 THIS MIGHTY STOCK WILL BE LIQUIDATED AT 27 CENTS ON THE DOLLAR 27\nStudy These Prices.\nMen's Clothing $8 00 suits all to match comes in worsteds and home spuns, this suit is positive-\nly ttrrSle. $1.50 goods for this eighty sale 89 cents.\nBoy's Two Piece Suits in a big variety of styles and elms to go quick, (9 cents.\nBoys' Knee Pants in a full line of sizes. 23 cent quality for 19 cents.\nChildren's Parasols, all colors to. close out for 19 cents.\nTodies' Umbrellas, 75 cent quality for 89 cents.\nSpecial-Ss' Wash Skirts, worth $1.50 and $2.00 98 Cents\nChfldren's Straw Hats 7 Cents, 12 and 19 worth double in each case.\nLadies' Street Hats, nicely trimmed $1 00 quality for 49 cents.\nLad es' -Saner Hats in black and white, while they last, 19 cents\nChiffon Panamas in a full line of colors special for this mighty sale. 21 cents\n5 000 yards of callicoes, strictly fast colors, 3 3-4 cents.\n5 000 yards apron gingham, 7 cent quality, 4 cents.\nWhite Indian linon, worth 12 cents, 7 cents.\nKungham lace curtain, 2 yards long, 75 cent quality for 4o cents,\nntpn towels e-enerous size, special for this sale, 4 cents.\nI0x whit 'bed spread regular dollar stuff, for this great sale, W cents\ni? 'rU- !hoes strong durable, fully guaranteed, $1.50 goods for $1.29.\nGOoVar of LadW shoesln (Sords, bluchers and Bals, part of a manufacturers stock in all the\nlat\" Sate. IS )ni brands as the Walkover, Dorothy\nDod Un Tpingree Gloria $3.50 and $4 00 goods, while they last, $1 .49.\nD lau cru. 4hnes 35 cent quality sale, price 19 cents.\nSS.\"wb5 l8 V'-rtft? 'ortWs miBhty8a,e' 29cents-\nJohn B. Stetaon Hals, for this mighty sale, S2.SW.\nExtra Special.\nMen's Rockford Half Hose, 10 cent quality for 4 cents.\nPeTrl Buttons, worth 5 cents, 2 cents per dozen.\nRki Buttons, white and smoked, 1 cent per dozen.\nPins, 1 cent sheet.\nHairpins, 3 cents per package.\nSafety Pins, 3 cents per dozen\nCrab Apple Soap, 3 cents a tablet.\nSleeve Holders, 3 cents a pair.\nMen Hose Supporters, 15 cent qty for 8 cents.\nSide Combs. 3 cents pair, worth 15 cents.\nBack Combs, 3 cents, worth 15 cent.\n75 cents and Jl match, worth 10 cents, 2 cents per yard.\nS'XX 'lit o enciene worth up to 10 cents per yard, for this mighty sale, 3 cents.\nbToeno Men .SaT- collars, 'all sizes for this great sale, 3 cents.\nJEFFERSON CITY. Mo.. May 20.\nGov. Joseph W. Folk and Tnited\nSlates Senator William J. Stone were\nunanimously elected delegates-at-large\nto the national democratic convention\nby the state democratic convention\nhere .today, and ex-Gov. David R.\nFrancis and ex-Mayor A. Reed, of\nKansas City, were elected as the other\ntwo delegates-at-large after a fight.\nImmediately after the election Sen\nator Stone arose and offered to de\ncline if the convention would elect as\ndelegate-at-large in his place Col.\nMoses C. Wetmore, cf St. Louis, who\nwas defeated for delegate-at-large.\nSenator Stone declared to the conven\ntion that Wetmore. is William Jen\nnings Bryan's closest friend in this\nState. A motion to adopt Senator\nStone's resignation received but few\nvotes.\nThese were elected alternates:\nMoses C. Wetmore, ex-Gov. Alex M.\nDockery, ex-Gov. Thomas T. Critten\nden and ex-Gov. Leon V. Stephens.\nNational ommitteeman W. A. Roth\nwell, of Sedalia, was re-elected after\nMoses C. Wetmore withdrew.\nResolutions were unanimously adop\nted instructing the delegates to sup\nport William Jennigs Bryan for presi\ndent as a unit. The convention adop\nted resolutions favoring the \"lakes to\nthe gulf deep waterway\" project and\ndenounced Missouri republicans for\ndeclaring state moneys had been\nsquandered before they fixed control,\nafter which they found all state mon\neys accounted for.\n.We guarantee every garment, every price and every state-\n0 Guarantee-ment herein made, ggJnSg\nfund your money on all unsatisfactory purchases. DON T FORGET THE OPENIWU\nDATEST May 28th, and look for the red front.\ni; GEORGE\n9\nADDRESS BY JOHN\nTROTWOOD MOORE\nBEFORE GRADUATE CLUB AND\nSTUDENTS OF VANDERBILT\nf UNIVERSITY.\nNASHVILLE, Tenn., May 19. Last\nnight in Furman Hall, before the mem\nbers of the Graduate Club and other\nRtudenta of the University, John Trot-\nwood Moore made a very forceful ad\ndress on the practical side of litera\nture.\nHe said that the literature of the\nsouth must have a national note if It\nis to hold its own with the literature\nof the world. He referred to the pros-\nnective nassine of the American fleet\nthrough the Continent ditch, and the\nfuture conflict with the yellow race\nas subjects for national literature.\nIn speaking of the practical side of\nliterature Mr. Moore discussed his\nsubject from two phases; first, the\ncompensation; second, the field.\n\"The present age is a practical one,\"\nhe said, \"and we ask the question,\nCan we make a living in the field of\nliterature? There was atime when\nthe best writers had no compensation,\nbut today the writer of a first class\nnovel often makes more money in one\nyear than the President of the republic\n\"While compensation Is great, there\nshould be no selfish motive on the\npart of a writer for money. Excel\nlence should be the first thought and\nwork done for the love of it. Of the\nthree great original American writers,\nthe South has furnished two Poe and\nLanier. These the south starved, but\nfor such writers today there will be\nample compensation.\"\nMr. Moore said the south might\nlook barren as a literary field, but it\nhad not really been touched. Like the\nphosphate of Middle Tennessee the\ncoal of the Birmingham mountains\nand the water power of the rivers, the\nvast opportunities In this Held ol\nliterature were yet to be realized.\n\"The true writer should paint things,\"\nbe said, \"as he sees them and not as\nsome one else sees them. Shake\nspeare's greatness was due to his pow\ner of assimilation. Bacon could not\nhave written the plays we have as\ncribed to Shakespeare for in him the\npower was wanting. Every great\nwriter is In one sense a plagiarist, that\nis he Is' able to take the thought of\nanother and glorify it.\n\"The South is a great field since an\nold civilization with its chivalry and\ntradition has passed into history and\na new life with new conditions has\nasserted itself. The problem of child\nlabor and the negro problem are to\nbe solved in the South and as yet tbe\nnovel is untouched.\"\nAt the close of his address Mr.\nMoore read several of his dialect\nstories.\nMT. PLEASANT, TENN.\n(NOTATIONS ON\nLOCAL MARKETS\nALL COMMODITIES REMAIN FIRM\nWITHOUT MARKED CHANGES\nIN PRICES.\nBig Increase in Trading. Wholesalers\nUnusually Busy. Retail\ners Busy.\nCOLUMBIA, Tenn., May 21. Trad\ning as a rule was good in all branches\nof business today. Commodities are\nfirm at marks. Egg shipments large\nwith price firm.\nThe two National Banks make tate\nnieuts and show a decided increase in\nthe deposits over their last statement\na few months, since. Both banks\nshow an abundance of money on baud\nand good loans, business outlook is\nimproving each day.\nLOUISVILLE LIVE STOCK.\nSpecial to The HeraM\nLOUISVILLE, Ky., May 21. Cattle\nmarket weak. Shipping cattle $5.50\n6.50; best butchers, $5.00'3$6.00; me\ndiums, $4.50 $5.00; commons, $3.00&\n$4.00; feeders, $4.00$5.00; stockers,\n$2.50(5 $4.50; balls, $2.00$4.50; can-\nuers, $1.00$2 25. Hogs Receipts 2,-'\n5S1 Heavy and medium, $5.40; lights,\n$5.30; pigs, 90 to 120, $3.25&$4.50;\nroughs, $4.75 down. Sheep and\nLambs Best lambs, $5.00$6.00; few\nspring lambs at $7.00 $8.00; best\nsheep, $4,506 $5.00.\nLOCAL LIVE STOCK.\nCOLUMBIA, Tenn., May 21. To\nday's local quotations follow: Best\nshipping cattle 1,000 to 1,200, $5.0\n$5.25; mediums, $3.50$4.25; com\nmons, $2.25r$3.10; feeders and stock\ners, $3.50$4.25; bulls. $2.50$3.50.\nHogs Market steady Heavy and me\ndium, $3.85; lights, $4.00; pigs,\n$2.85$3.00; roughs, $3.00 down\nSheep and Lambs Best lambs, $4.00\n$5.00; best sheep, $4.00.\nFIELD SEED.\n(Quotations by Callender ft Co.)\nOats From farmers' hands, 65c per\nbu. From store, 65a\nClover From farmers balds, $8.6'.\n$9.00 per bu. Northern' seed, from\nstores, $9.50$12-60.\nCane Seed From farmer's hands\n85c per bu. From store, $1.25 per bu.\nBlue Grass From stores, $2.50 per\nbu.\nOrchard Grass $2.20 per bu.\nTimothy $2.05; Red Top, 10c lb.\nWhipporwlll Peas Jjorn farmers\nhands, $1.60; at stores, $1.95.\nJUNK, RUBBER, ZINC AND LEAD.\n(Quotations furnished by Louis\nBarker.)\nOld scrap iron 15c to 20c per hun\ndred. Brass Heavy brass 6c lb;\nlight brass, 3c lb. Copper Light cop\nper, 6c lb; heavy copper, 8c lb.\nBones 20c to 25c per hundred.\nRubber Rubber tires, 4c lb; No. 1\nshoes, 3c lb; No. 2 shoes, l'Jc lb.\nZinc lc lb. Lead 2c lb.\nWHOLESALE PRODUCE.\n(Quotations furnished by S. E. Cal\nender ft Co.\nCabbage Southern stock large\ncrates, $1.90$2.00 per crate.\nPotatoes Irish eating stock, $2.7\nper bag.\nAlabama Snap Beans $1.50 per crate\nBananas Jumbos, per buoch, $1.25\n$1.75; extra large, $2.00 per bunch\nAnnies WinesaD. fancy per bbl.,\n$4.50; N. Y. Baldwins, per bbl., $4.50\nTomatoes Florida Btock, $2.00 per\ncrate.\nOranges Per box, $3.40.\nLemons Fancy, $4.00.\nOnion Sets At stores, $1.75 bu;\neating onions at store. 80c bu.\nWhite Peas $3.50 bu.; Navy beans.\n2.C5sbu.; Lima BeanB, 6c lb.\nCheese White Clover. 15c lb.\nFLOUR AND GRAIN.\n(Quotations furnished by ColumbU\nMill Elevator Co., and Ashton''\nMills.)\nFlour Best Patent, $5.25; second\nPatent, $4.75; Bran, per ton, $25.\nMeal at mills, 80c bu. in bulk; 85c\nsacked; old corn, per bbl., $3.50;\nWheat $1.00$1.05.\nPRODUCE.\nJ (Tfct. i,uui.i.ii ai toroisb by\nj ,Vbi. Pfc. ktr\nEpgs and Puu.lrr Eg, psr extern.\nUc loose and firm; Hens, 9c lb;\n.;rtilf-rs. 15c If. anj in great demand;\nTurkeys. Sc tb; Ducks. 10c lb.\nLutvi Chiles country, 12c lb and\nf f'.:.\nWOOL.\n(Quotations by L. Barker.)\nYimI Tubwasbel, 12c lb; nn-wj-.tlid\ns:rin free from burrs, 15c;\nSlisr'ly b iry, 12c; medium burry 8c\nft l'V hard burry, Gc7c.\nHIDES, GINSENG, FPATHERS ETC.\nQuotations by L. Barker.)\nHides Green 4c lb; cured, 4V&0\nlb; dry salt hides, 7c lb; flint, 9o\nHj. Horse hiaes No 1 large, $1.75;\nNo. 2, $1.00Q $1.50; mule hides Large,\n$1.50; small, $1 00.\nGoat Skins, 15c; lamb skins, 20;\nclippers skins, 10; wool Bkins, 25c\n40c\nGinseng Dry, $5.00; green 85c\n$1.00. Yellow root $1.00.\nFeathers New eonse feathers 40\nlb; old goose feathers, 25c 35c D;\nmixed. lf,cjr??.\"c lb- duck feathers,\n20c35o lb. i\nBeeswax 22c lb.\nTallow 4c lb; caked tallow, 40.\nSubscribe for Ths Hsrald.\nBACON, LARD AND PRE3H MEATS\nTbese quotations are furnished r\nM. S. King)\nBacon From farmers' bands-\nHams, 10cllc per lb; Sides, 8c\ni n n,, mnt,at n aHvq\nid; snouiaers, se usal a\"\nLard Pure country, 9c lb. In tins.\nRetail grocers ars paying and sell\nIng country bacon at the followlnr\nnrlces:\nfarmers' hands Hams. 10c\nper P! Sides, 8c per lb; Shoulders\n7c per lb; Lard, i per lb.\nSelling to the trade Hams, MH\n1; Sides, llc per lb; Shoulder\n(0c per lb; Lard, Ultc per lb.\nfresh Meats At Store Beef\nSteaks, lOcflMJHc: Prk. efll!Hr\nper lb; Roast meats. Sc91!tt Pr\nWHOLESALE GROCERIES\n(Quotations furnished by J. A.\nSloan Co.)\nSugar Best Boston graulated sug\nar, 100 lbs., $5.80; Brown Sugar, $5.50\nper hundred.\nLard Leaf, unsettled st 11c lb;\nCompound, &c lb.\nCoffee Bulk roast. llVicjj27tte;\nGreen, 9c14tte\nPITCHED BATTLE\nAT TOLL GATE\nATTEMPT IS MADE TO ASSASSIN\nATE THOMAS M. HART AND\nHIS SON.\nGATES WERE TORN DOWN BY MOB\nMany Raids Have Been Made at\nSame Place in The\nPast.\nNASHVILLE. Tenn., May 20.\nAbout twenty-five or thirty armed\nmen raided the toll gate on the Nash\nville and Goodlettsville turnpike about\n2 o'clock yesterday morning, and la\nter in the day a pitched battle, In\nwhich Thomas 2.1. Hart, his son, Thom\nas Hart, Jr., and Arthur Morton, the\ntoll gate keeper, two of whom were\narmed with Winchester rifles, and the\nother with a shotgun, held at bay a\nmob of about fifteen men armed with\nshotguns.\nMr. Morton went to the residence\nof Mr. Harr, who owns the turnpike in\nSumner county, and reported to him\nthe raid\" made on the toll gate early\nyesterday morning. The toll gate is\nlocated in Sumner- county at a little\nvillage called Millersville, about two\nmiles from the Davidson county line,\nand is the only toll gate on the road.\nWith three miles of the road in this\ncounty the turnpike was purchased byi\nMr. Hart about six years ago. The\nportion of the road in Davidson coun\nty he sold to this county, retaining\nsix and a half miles of road in Sum\nrer county. Since Mr. Hart acquired\nthe property raids have been made on\nIt, bridges have been dynamited, an\nattempt to burn a bridge made and\nthe toll gate keepers have been warned\nby anonymous letters to abstain' from\nattempting to collect toll.\nHe gave me a bogus primary under\nwhich, by tbe bribery of a few bums\nand vagabonds, every honest and In\ncorruptible democrat. in the county\nmay be bought, sold and delivered to\nthe corruptlonist.\nNONRESIDENT NOTICE.\nCterk and MRtrr'- Office, Columbia,\nTenn., May 22nd. 1908.\nMinnie Williams Brlggs, et Com\nplnlnants,\nvs.\nW. 8. Fleming, Ex'rt. et al. Defendants.\nIt appearing from affidavit filed In\nthis cause, thRt the Defendants, Cor\nnelia Winder. Ellen McConnachie,\nJohn McConnachie. John Pugh. Pres\nton Piifh. inward Vn. AMan Pugh,\nCatherine Pugh, Lo Willie Landers,\nW. G. Landers Bettle Sanford and\nMary R. Looney, are non-residents of\nthe State of Tennessee.\nIt is therefore ordered that they\nenter (heir appearance herein, before\nor within the first three days of the\nnext term of the Chancery' Court, to\nbe held at Columbia, on the first\nMonday In July next, 1908. and plead,\nnnswer. or demur to Complainant's\nbill, or the same will b taken for con-1\nfossed as to Ihem and set for hearing\nex parte; and that a copy of this or\nder be published for four 'consecutive\nweeks In thr Columbia Herald.\nA Copy-Attt:\nA. N. AKIN. Clerk and Master.\nCART'THERS EWING and\nE. H. A C. P. HATCHER.\nSol'rs. for Compl't.\n!2-4t I ..J\ni","height":"28280","width":"19644"}}
